<methodology slug="spec-examples-basic">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>sdd</group>
    <domain>sdd-planning</domain>
    <summary>Condensed spec for MVP features: Problem Statement, User Stories (max 3), FR (Must only), AC (happy path + error case), Out of Scope. Typical size: 1100–1650 tokens.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>spec</tag>
      <tag>condensed</tag>
      <tag>mvp</tag>
      <tag>example</tag>
      <tag>sdd</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>example</category>
    <difficulty>beginner</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Specification Examples: Basic</title>
    <summary>Condensed spec format for MVP features with clear, well-understood requirements. Reduces the full spec-structure v2.0 to five minimum sections: Problem Statement, User Stories (max 3), Functional Requirements (Must only), Acceptance Criteria (1 happy path + 1 error), Out of Scope. Typical size: 1100–1650 tokens.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Full spec-structure v2.0 adds overhead (detailed personas, NFR tables, open questions) that is unjustified for simple CRUD operations or well-known patterns. The condensed format preserves traceability (FR → US → AC) while eliminating sections that carry no new information at MVP scope. Because the condensed spec fits in 1-2k tokens, agents can include it in full context without budget pressure.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>MVP features with clear requirements (≤ 5 FRs, ≤ 3 User Stories).</item>
        <item>Simple CRUD operations or well-known patterns (auth, registration, forms).</item>
        <item>Small team, fast iteration environment.</item>
        <item>Proof of concept or rapid prototyping.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Features with multiple user personas and complex business rules — use spec-structure full v2.0 instead.</item>
        <item>Regulated domains (payments, healthcare, legal) where traceability completeness is non-negotiable.</item>
        <item>Features with more than 5 User Stories or 10 Functional Requirements.</item>
        <item>Security-sensitive features where at least an unauthorized-access AC is required (condensed ACs are too thin).</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="minimum-viable-sections">
      <rule>
        <statement>A condensed spec must include exactly these five sections: Problem Statement, User Stories (max 3), Functional Requirements (Must only), Acceptance Criteria (1 happy path + 1 error case), Out of Scope.</statement>
        <rationale>These five sections preserve traceability (FR traces to US, AC validates FR) while eliminating overhead that adds no new information at MVP scope.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Write Out of Scope immediately after User Stories — before writing FRs. This prevents scope creep from accumulating before requirements are defined.</statement>
        <rationale>Out of Scope written last tends to be incomplete. Written second, it explicitly bounds what the FRs must NOT address.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="token-budget">
      <p>Typical condensed spec size by section:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Problem Statement: 100-200 tokens</item>
        <item>User Stories (3 max): 300-400 tokens</item>
        <item>Functional Requirements (5 max): 200-300 tokens</item>
        <item>Acceptance Criteria (2-3 scenarios): 400-600 tokens</item>
        <item>Out of Scope: 100-150 tokens</item>
        <item>Total: 1100-1650 tokens</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>A condensed spec must stay under 80 lines. Use wc -l as a quick size check before committing.</statement>
        <rationale>Condensed specs that grow past 80 lines are no longer condensed — they have absorbed full-spec content and should be upgraded to spec-structure v2.0.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="authentication-example">
      <example type="good" title="User Authentication (MVP)">
        <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[# Feature: User Authentication

**Version:** 1.0
**Status:** Approved
**Project:** cashflow-planner

## Reference Documents
| Document | Path |
|----------|------|
| Constitution | `.aidocs/constitution.md` |

## Problem Statement
**Who:** New users of the cashflow planning app
**Problem:** Cannot access personal financial data because there is no authentication
**Impact:** Users cannot save cashflow projections, blocking core value proposition
**Solution:** Email-based authentication with JWT
**Success Metric:** 1000 registered users in first month

## User Stories

### US-001: Email Registration (MVP)
**As a** financial planner
**I want to** create an account with my email
**So that** I can save and access my cashflow projections
**Priority:** Must
**Acceptance Criteria:** AC-001, AC-002

## Functional Requirements

| ID | Requirement | Traces To | Priority |
|----|-------------|-----------|----------|
| FR-001 | System SHALL allow registration with email + password | US-001 | Must |
| FR-002 | System SHALL validate email format (RFC 5322) | US-001 | Must |
| FR-003 | System SHALL require password min 8 chars, 1 upper, 1 number | US-001 | Must |

## Acceptance Criteria

### AC-001: Successful Registration
**Given:** User is on registration page
**When:** User enters valid email and valid password
**Then:** Account is created
**And:** User receives verification email within 30 seconds
**And:** User is redirected to dashboard

### AC-002: Registration with Existing Email
**Given:** Email "test@example.com" exists in system
**When:** User tries to register with "test@example.com"
**Then:** Error message "Email already registered" is displayed
**And:** No duplicate account is created

## Out of Scope

| Feature | Reason | When |
|---------|--------|------|
| Social login | Not MVP | Phase 2 |
| 2FA | Complexity | Phase 3 |]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="fr-language-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every Functional Requirement must use "System SHALL [specific, testable action]" language. Exclude ambiguous verbs: support, handle, manage, validate (when the validation rule is not specified).</statement>
        <rationale>Ambiguous FRs produce ambiguous ACs. "System SHALL validate email" is testable only if the validation rule is stated — "System SHALL validate email format (RFC 5322)" is testable.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Specific, testable FR">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[System SHALL allow registration with email + password]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="bad" title="Verbose, ambiguous FR">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[The system shall provide users with the ability to create a new account using their email address and a secure password that meets our security requirements]]></code>
        <note>Verbose, ambiguous "security requirements". Rewrite as a short SHALL statement with explicit criteria.</note>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="traceability-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every FR must trace to exactly one User Story. Every AC must validate at least one FR. Orphaned FRs and orphaned ACs are quality gate failures.</statement>
        <rationale>Traceability lets the executor agent verify coverage mechanically: every Must-priority FR has an AC that passes, therefore the feature satisfies its user stories.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Condense spec traceability to the FR table (Traces To column) and the US Acceptance Criteria field. No separate traceability matrix needed at condensed scale.</statement>
        <rationale>A separate matrix adds overhead that the condensed format is designed to avoid. The table columns carry sufficient traceability for 3-5 FRs.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="ac-format-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>All ACs must use Given-When-Then format with specific values (not "valid email" but "test@example.com"). A condensed spec needs exactly one happy path AC and one error case AC.</statement>
        <rationale>ACs without specific values cannot be mechanically verified. "User enters valid email" passes any input; "User enters test@example.com" passes only the correct input.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>AC items that read as requirements: "User can register with email and password."</description>
        <reason>Not a scenario — has no Given, When, Then. Cannot be verified as pass or fail. Rewrite as a Given-When-Then scenario.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="scale-escape-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>If the agent produces more than 3 User Stories or more than 6 Functional Requirements, the feature is not "basic". Escalate to full spec-structure v2.0.</statement>
        <rationale>A condensed spec with 8 FRs is not condensed — it is a full spec with missing sections. The missing sections (NFRs, detailed personas, Open Questions) will cause problems in later phases.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents adding "Technical Notes" or "Architecture" sections to a condensed spec.</description>
        <reason>These belong in design.md. The spec answers WHAT and WHY only. Reject these sections at review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Omitting the Out of Scope section entirely.</description>
        <reason>Without explicit scope boundaries, any omitted feature becomes an implicit requirement. Out of Scope prevents implementation debates.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/spec-size-check.sh" purpose="Bash script: counts US, FR, AC in a spec file and warns when counts exceed condensed-format thresholds."/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
